g:<goal> Determine the factual accuracy of the claim "Humans use only 10% of their brain" and provide a calibrated confidence score based on scientific consensus and evidence.</goal>;
c:<constraints> No creative writing or summarization. Must show reasoning chain. Must address the question directly without padding. Confidence score must be 0-100.</constraints>;
s:<steps> 1. Identify the scientific consensus on brain utilization (neuroimaging, lesion studies, functional mapping). 2. Evaluate the origin and nature of the "10% myth." 3. Assess the magnitude of evidence against the claim. 4. Assign a confidence score based on the weight of evidence.</steps>;
r:<reasoning> The claim "Humans use only 10% of their brain" is a pervasive myth. Neuroimaging techniques (fMRI, PET, EEG) consistently show that nearly all parts of the brain are active even during "rest" (the default mode network), and different areas light up depending on the task. Lesion studies demonstrate that damage to almost any part of the brain results in some form of deficit, implying every region has a function. There is no credible scientific evidence supporting the idea that 90% of the brain is non-functional or unused. The consensus in neuroscience is overwhelming and uniform against this claim. Therefore, the claim is false.</reasoning>

**Claim:** Humans use only 10% of their brain.
**Verdict:** False.
**Confidence Score:** 100/100
